# Procedure Topic: Recruitment  
## Standardized Onboarding & Early Momentum Procedure (Week 0 → First Contribution)

Jimmy Hoang

---

## Problem Statement

Onboarding and early ramp-up across HAAG teams is inconsistent. New researchers (and computational advisors) can lose momentum early due to unclear expectations, uneven documentation, and delays in access/setup. Common friction points include:

- No shared “Week 0” standard for what must be defined up front (goals, repos, access, readings, first tasks)
- Access/setup steps that aren’t centralized, causing back-and-forth
- Unclear expectations for computational advisor involvement and accountability loops
- Slow transition from onboarding → meaningful work, which can set a low-momentum tone for the semester

This initiative focuses on standardizing onboarding so new members can get productive faster and teams can start moving earlier.

---

## Initiative Goal

Design and evaluate a lightweight onboarding procedure that helps new HAAG members ramp up quickly and consistently across teams.

**Deliverables**
- A documented onboarding procedure that can be reused each semester
- A “Week 0 Onboarding Packet” template (one-page checklist + links)
- A simple rollout guide for project managers / admins

---

# Initiative Framework

## 1. Discovery

To understand the current onboarding workflow and bottlenecks, I will:

- Review existing onboarding materials and references (Slack/Wiki/Canvas and any team docs)
- Capture how different teams currently handle:
  - Goals and scope clarity
  - Access requirements (tools, repos, datasets)
  - Expected onboarding readings / background material
  - Team communication norms and first tasks
- Interview a small set of stakeholders (admins/TAs, project managers, researchers, and computational advisors) to learn:
  - What slowed onboarding the most
  - What information people wish they had on Day 1
  - Which steps create repeated admin overhead

This phase outputs a short “current state map” of onboarding steps and recurring failure points.

---

## 2. Hypothesis

If HAAG adopts a standardized “Week 0 Onboarding Packet” and checklist that every team completes before (or immediately after) new members join, then:

- New members will understand expectations earlier
- Access/setup will complete faster with fewer follow-up messages
- Teams will reach a first meaningful task/commit sooner
- Admin overhead from repeated clarification will decrease

---

## 3. Experiment – Pilot + Walkthrough Review

If a live onboarding cycle is available, I will pilot this procedure with 1–2 teams. If not, I will run a structured walkthrough evaluation using stakeholders and past onboarding scenarios.

### Procedure

1. **Create a Week 0 Onboarding Packet template** (single source of truth) containing:
   - Project goals (1–3 bullets)
   - Required access list (accounts, repos, datasets, tools)
   - Repo map (which repos matter + what each is for)
   - Required onboarding readings (short list + links)
   - Communication cadence (meetings, async norms, response expectations)
   - Computational advisor expectations (level of involvement, review loop)
   - “First task menu” (2–5 starter tasks sized for early contribution)

2. **Run the pilot or walkthrough**
   - Pilot: give the template to participating teams and have them use it for onboarding
   - Walkthrough: simulate the perspective of a new joiner reading the packet and completing setup

3. **Collect feedback**
   - Ask: What was unclear? What’s missing? What feels redundant?
   - Identify any repeated confusion points and revise the template/procedure

---

## 4. Metrics for Evaluation

Success will be measured using a small set of practical indicators:

- **Time to access complete** (acceptance → all required access granted)
- **Time to first meaningful task/commit** (access complete → first real contribution)
- **Clarity score** from quick stakeholder feedback (e.g., “Was it obvious what to do next?”)
- **Reduction in back-and-forth** (qualitative: fewer repeated clarification messages)

If the procedure reduces ambiguity and improves early momentum without adding heavy overhead, it will be considered effective.

---

## 5. Report & Iterate

After the pilot / walkthrough:

- Summarize findings and note the biggest onboarding bottlenecks
- Revise the onboarding packet template and checklist
- Produce the finalized onboarding procedure and a short implementation guide
- Recommend where this should live (shared repo/docs) and who owns updating it each semester

---

## Intended Audience

- HAAG admins / TAs  
- Project managers / team leads  
- Computational advisors  
- Faculty advisors (visibility into who is onboarded + contributing)

---

## Organizational Need Being Served

This initiative supports faster, more consistent onboarding and protects early-semester momentum. It also improves continuity across semesters by ensuring key project information is documented in a reusable, standardized format.
